I really wanted to like this place but I will not be back. Based on reviews, I was expecting a slow service which it was but that is not the problem.  The concern I have is the food safety.  The Senegalese Egg roll was hot outside but the center was cold. So when you bite into it, you felt a frozen crunch. It made me wonder if the food was cooked long enough especially since the waitress could not tell me what kind of meat was used (“I don’t know but it is good” is what she said.)  Also the lamb dish I ordered had a string of hair. With frozen egg roll and a string of hair, I lost my appetite and became concern about food safety.

Very good food at a good price.  First off, the restaurant picture on Google is not correct - the restaurant is a far more cosy, darker affair with fitting music. It doesn't look at that much from the front but we were comfortable and it was clean. The servers were lovely and friendly too helping us through the menu.  Second, the food was great. The menu was a little reduced as it was a Sunday and there were a number of things they had run out of (a lot of takeaway meals were prepared whilst we were there). Nonetheless we both found something to order. All traditional Senegalese dishes with various meats or fish. I had chicken skewers which were flavoured beautifully, accompanied by some Vermicelli and fried plantain. My partner had a grilled fish.  Overall it all tasted great and we paid about 40 dollars in total which is very good value for the portion - neither of us finished and we eat a lot! Cash or card, however, make sure you have both (there are a few signs that warn you to!) Would definitely recommend.

A must try in the heart of the Bronx. Was in NY for a week, looking for a nice West African restaurant and searched on Google and Found a place in the Bronx named Chez Asta. Went to the address but couldn't find such place. Called number and turns out the place just changed the name to Chez Jacob. Same address same everything. The food is as authentic as it comes and tasty and pretty cheap compared to the quality you receive. I saw a mention of customer service, it is true it's not your typical customer service where they try to anticipate your needs so don't be afraid to just raise your hand and get the attention of the cashier/waitress working and she will oblige. They are otherwise very nice people and the ambience is on point. Take that trip to Senegal with your palate, sens of smell and hearing. Don't forget to try their homemade drinks, one made with ginger root juiced, or the other made with Hibiscus flower (red) infusion. Both served cold. A must try in the heart of the Bronx.
